04516nam a22005895i 9780520929159DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20042005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209291597 a10.1525/97805209291592doi  a(DE-B1597)518966  a(OCoLC)475933700  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML2633.2 .M33 2004eb 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a782.4309451 aMcClary, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModal Subjectivities :bSelf-Fashioning in the Italian Madrigal /cSusan McClary. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (386 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tExamples -- tAcknowledgments -- tOne. Introduction: The Cultural Work of the Madrigal -- tTwo. Night and Deceit: Verdelot's Machiavelli -- tThree. The Desiring Subject, or Subject to Desire: Arcadelt -- tFour. Radical Inwardness: Willaert's Musica nova -- tFive. The Prisonhouse of Mode: Cipriano de Rore -- tSix. A Coney Island of the Madrigal: Wert and Marenzio -- tSeven. The Luxury of Solipsism: Gesualdo -- tEight. The Mirtillo/Amarilli Controversy: Monteverdi -- tNine. I modi -- tAppendix: Examples -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this boldly innovative book, renowned musicologist Susan McClary presents an illuminating cultural interpretation of the Italian madrigal, one of the most influential repertories of the Renaissance. A genre that sought to produce simulations in sound of complex interiorities, the madrigal introduced into music a vast range of new signifying practices: musical representations of emotions, desire, gender stereotypes, reason, madness, tensions between mind and body, and much more. In doing so, it not only greatly expanded the expressive agendas of European music but also recorded certain assumptions of the time concerning selfhood, making it an invaluable resource for understanding the history of Western subjectivity. Modal Subjectivities covers the span of the sixteenth-century polyphonic madrigal, from its early manifestations in Philippe Verdelot's settings of Machiavelli in the 1520s through the tortured chromatic experiments of Carlo Gesualdo. Although McClary takes the lyrics into account in shaping her readings, she focuses particularly on the details of the music itself-the principal site of the genre's self-fashionings. In order to work effectively with musical meanings in this pretonal repertory, she also develops an analytical method that allows her to unravel the sophisticated allegorical structures characteristic of the madrigal. This pathbreaking book demonstrates how we might glean insights into a culture on the basis of its nonverbal artistic enterprises.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMadrigals, ItalianxAnalysis, appreciationx16th centuryxItaly. 0aMadrigals, ItalianzItalyy16th centuryxAnalysis, appreciation. 0aMusic and language. 0aMusic theoryxHistoryx16th century. 0aMusic theoryxHistoryy16th century. 0aMusical formxHistoryx16th century. 0aMusical formxHistoryy16th century. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520929159.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles